{
  "text": "(1) The corresponding statement for the spaces H 1/2,\u03c1 and H 3/2,\u03c1 is also true, but a little less interesting. Since there are no unary theta functions for\u03c1, it just says that a weakly holomorphic modular form of weight 1/2 or 3/2 for \u03c1, whose principal part is defined over K, has coefficients in K up to addition of a cusp form. This follows immediatly from the fact that the spaces M ! 1/2,\u03c1 and M ! 3/2,\u03c1 have bases with rational coefficients (see [CITATION_1] ). (2) We have formulated the theorem using vector valued modular forms for the Weil representation since it best suits our applications. In view of Remark 2.2 the theorem implies a rationality result for the \u03be-preimages of the scalar valued theta series \u03b8 \u03c8,m (\u03c4 ) as well. (3) The holomorphic projection method developed in [CITATION_2] yields a recursive formula for the coefficients of the holomorphic part of f . It should also be possible to prove the above theorem using this technique.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "122421429",
    "[CITATION_2]": "10894708"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "10894708": {
      "title": "Holomorphic projections and Ramanujan's mock theta functions",
      "abstract": "We employ spectral methods of automorphic forms to establish a holomorphic projection operator for tensor products of vector-valued harmonic weak Maass forms and vector-valued modular forms. We apply this operator to discover simple recursions for Fourier series coefficients of Ramanujan's mock theta functions."
    },
    "122421429": {
      "title": "The rationality of vector valued modular forms associated with the Weil representation",
      "abstract": "In a recent paper [Duke Math. J., 97, 219\u2013233], Borcherds asks whether or not the spaces of vector valued modular forms associated to the Weil representation have bases of modular forms whose Fourier expansions have only integer coefficients. We give an affirmative answer to Borcherds' question. This strengthens and simplifies Borcherds' main theorem which is a generalization of a theorem of Gross, Kohnen, and Zagier [Math. Ann., 278, 497\u2013562]."
    }
  }
}